en atom,<br /><br /><math><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>E</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mo>=</mo></math> <math><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math><br /><br />Thus, it is obvious that the hydrogen atom has some characteristics of energy state. In fact, this is true for the atom of each element, <math><mi>i</mi><mi>e</mi><mo>,</mo></math> each atom has its energy quantized.<br />Hence, both energy and angular momentum are quantised.", "image": null}, "videoSolution": null, "numericalLowerLimit": null, "numericalUpperLimit": null, "cpyqbSubjects": ["61bb58181213731910ea0b70", "61c055eae8ce0dc8a5c62d33", "616057750283de43c87e3e1b", "61964fe0a5a5260118868021", "61964f81a5a526011886801d", "629f39e4ac11b26562e0625b", "616057920283de43c87e3e1e", "615f0c729476412f48314dab", "61a8a2c2e8ce0dc8a5c62d2d", "629105adee9e3ae00d63352b", "629f385f263330a77be9fa7d", "616056cd0283de43c87e3e15", "616057190283de43c87e3e18", "62962075e7f8e9ac4daeafd7", "64d50bd73df7f4a7f3017f6f", "66b79b34d4b564dfab4f94cc", "678ea9a09cc79e5f592bdc11", "67fa5fef4468eb1307ceb0ad", "6807d2ad647479b8e8696479"], "cpyqbChapters": ["6160244defc76de5773f3b04", "6160244db8c481525a1215ef", "6160244cb4f517cc680aa439", "61964c95f3d02062bde4be67", "61e7bd7f77a4ea0f853aa953", "6160244b2069b4ac8ab389b4", "61c089b72898f7e4ea712965", "6160244ea9c7f3586ff3388b", "61bb822a5f69d75f5f0ee9ea", "61964c95f72a9436d4897955", "629109eac170f867f214b337", "629f3a8f9b4bccc32c98